Appendix D: Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)

Q1: Can I use the Software inside my company?
A1: Yes, provided that the usage is for Non‑Commercial Purposes (such as internal technical research, testing, and evaluation), and not for any commercial operations or revenue‑generating activities.

Q2: Can I integrate the Software into my open‑source project?
A2: Yes, provided that your project as a whole is Non‑Commercial in nature and also complies with the terms of this License.

Q3: Can I use the Software for teaching?
A3: Yes, teaching is a Non‑Commercial Purpose, but you may not charge fees directly related to the Software.

Q4: What if I want to use the Software for a commercial project?
A4: Please contact the Licensor via GitHub or email to obtain a Commercial License.

Q5: If I find a vulnerability in the Software, may I disclose it publicly?
A5: It is recommended to first report the vulnerability to the Licensor and wait for it to be fixed before public disclosure, to avoid security risks.

Q6: Can I modify the Software and publish my modified version?
A6: Yes, but you must comply with the distribution conditions of this License, including retaining copyright notices, documenting modifications, and attaching a copy of the License.

Q7: What is the difference between this License and the MIT License?
A7: The MIT License permits commercial use, whereas this License expressly prohibits commercial use and requires complete retention of license notices and modification records.

Q8: Can I display the Software on my website?
A8: Yes, provided that the website does not involve commercial activities (such as charging fees, displaying advertisements, etc.).

Q9: The Software contains third‑party code; do I need to comply with their licenses?
A9: Yes, you must comply with all third‑party code license terms.

Q10: Does donating to the project count as Commercial Purpose?
A10: Donation itself is generally not considered Commercial Purpose, provided that:
    (a) the donation is unrelated to the right to use the Software;
    (b) the donation does not constitute consideration for purchasing or subscribing to the Software;
    (c) the donation does not affect the fair and open availability of the Software to all users.

Q11: Is this License legally enforceable in Chinese courts?
A11: Yes. Chinese courts have indirectly recognized the legal validity of open‑source licenses in multiple cases. As a copyright license agreement with a resolutive condition, this License is enforceable under the Chinese legal framework.

Q12: Can I use the Software for artificial intelligence model training?
A12: No. Article 1.2 of this License expressly prohibits using the Software for any AI, machine learning, or large language model training.


Appendix E: Export Control and Data Protection Compliance Reference

This appendix provides compliance references for the latest regulatory developments in export control and data protection. It is not contractually binding — it serves as a practical compliance guide.

1. Export Control

| # | Regulation / Document | Effective / Updated | Key Points |
| :-: | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| 1 | Export Control Law of the PRC | Dec 1, 2020 | Establishes the basic export control system, covering controlled items, controlled activities, licensing, and extraterritorial jurisdiction |
| 2 | Regulations on the Export Control of Dual‑Use Items | 2024 | Refines the scope and control measures for dual‑use items |
| 3 | Dual‑Use Items Export Control List | Updated Oct 2025 | Specifies controlled items — licensees should periodically verify |
| 4 | Foreign Trade Law | Revised Mar 1, 2026 | Adds new export control‑related institutional arrangements |
| 5 | New Customs Declaration Rules | Apr–Jun 2026 | General Administration of Customs added two new declaration fields: “Restricted Control Identification Code” and “Restricted Control Declaration Elements” |
| 6 | U.S. Export Administration Regulations (EAR) & EU Sanctions Regulations | — | Must also be complied with if the Licensee is in or involves relevant jurisdictions |

Tip: Licensees should regularly check for updates from the Ministry of Commerce (www.mofcom.gov.cn) and the General Administration of Customs (www.customs.gov.cn).

2. Data Protection

| # | Regulation / Standard | Effective / Published | Key Points |
| :-: | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| 1 | Personal Information Protection Law (PIPL) | Nov 1, 2021 | Establishes personal information processing rules, regulates automated decision‑making and cross‑border transfers |
| 2 | Data Security Law | Sep 1, 2021 | Establishes a data classification and grading protection system, defines security obligations for important data processors |
| 3 | Cybersecurity Law | Jun 1, 2017 | Requires network operators to fulfill cybersecurity protection obligations |
| 4 | GB/T 46068‑2025 | Mar 1, 2026 | Technical standard for personal information export certification |
| 5 | Personal Information Export Certification Measures | Published Oct 2025 | Refines the personal information export certification mechanism |
| 6 | Provisions on Facilitating and Regulating Cross‑Border Data Flows | — | Clarifies circumstances exempt from declaration |

Three Compliance Paths for Personal Information Exports:
1. Declare for Data Export Security Assessment
2. Conclude a Standard Contract for Personal Information Export
3. Obtain Personal Information Protection Certification

Tip: Licensees should ensure a lawful basis for data processing activities and implement appropriate technical and organizational measures to safeguard data security. While the above national standards are not legally mandatory, they serve as best‑practice references for compliance.


